@flexiarg writing-coherence/subheading-without-paragraph
@title Discharge the Subheading's Claim
@keywords subheading, structure, promise, discharge, label, concept-drop
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/unearned-essentially]

! conclusion: A subheading is a promise that the following paragraph will make a specific claim.  When the paragraph names the concept but does not discharge the promise — two or three sentences that gesture at the label without stating what the label actually asserts — the subheading is a label looking for a paragraph, and the document's structural skeleton goes soft at that point.
  + context: AI drafts frequently produce subheadings that sound structural ("Ontogenetic accretion", "Architectural sustainability", "The recursive scaffold") but whose paragraphs merely restate the concept's existence.  The subheading commits to more than the text pays.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: structural promise ↔ content capacity.
    Real: a strong subheading carves the argument into inspectable units; an under-discharged subheading creates the appearance of structure without the argumentative weight.  Readers track subheadings as a proxy for what the paper claims.
    Irreducible: a subheading cannot both promise a claim and merely name a concept.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a writer has a strong concept name but hasn't yet written the paragraph that earns it.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Expand: discharge the promise.  Write the paragraph that makes the claim the subheading asserted.  If the concept is "ontogenetic accretion", walk the reader through what accretes, at which stage, from which prior deposit.
    (2) Fold: drop the subheading and merge the existing content into an adjacent section as a closing remark or bridge sentence.  Concept survives; structural promise retracts.
    (3) Rename: replace the ambitious subheading with one that matches the claim actually present.  If the paragraph says "each stage depends on prior stages", the subheading should say that, not "ontogenetic accretion".
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: reader can state the subheading's claim in one sentence, independent of the subheading, drawn from the paragraph body.  Failing when: the only sentence that makes the claim is the subheading itself.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Concept-drop: the subheading names a concept; the paragraph says the concept is important.
    - Two-sentence stub: a paragraph of two sentences under a subheading, neither of which states a claim.
    - Restatement: the paragraph restates the subheading in a full sentence and stops.
